facts.html: July-December. July 15 - The Narragansett tribe signs a peace treaty with Connecticut.
January-March. March 1 - North German Confederation issues 10gr and 30gr value stamps, printed on goldbeater's skin.

January-March. January 16 - A resolution is passed in the German Parliament, to condemn the Prussian deportations, the politically motivated mass expulsion of ethnic Poles and Jews from Prussia, initiated by Otto von Bismarck.
The University of Mississippi is founded.
By area Europe. In the Peerage of England, the title Baron de Ros, the oldest continuously held peerage title in England, is created by writ of summons.
October-December. October 1 - Weather Bureau (within Department of Agriculture).
Asia. Pelusium is razed by Baldwin I of Jerusalem.
January-March March 5. George Westinghouse receives a United States patent for the "failsafe" automatic railway air brake.
Kew Gardens established in England by Augusta of Saxe-Coburg, the mother of George III.
Europe. Lisbon becomes the capital of the Kingdom of Portugal.
Alfred Wegener publishes his theory of Pangaea.
July-December. July 26 - New York ratifies the United States Constitution and becomes the eleventh U.S. state.
September 16 - Thorstein Olafssøn marries Sigrid Bjørnsdatter in Hvalsey Church, in the last recorded event of the Norse history of Greenland.
October-December. October 6 - Rome becomes the capital of unified Italy.

July-December. September 14 - Flight of the Earls: Hugh O'Neill, 2nd Earl of Tyrone, and Rory O'Donnell, 1st Earl of Tyrconnell, flee Ireland for Spain with ninety followers to avoid capture by the English crown, never to return.
January-March. January 8 - American Indian Wars - Battle of Wolf Mountain: Crazy Horse and his warriors fight their last battle with the United States Cavalry in Montana.
Edmund Sutton, English nobleman (b. 1425)
Robert Boyle publishes Nova experimenta physico-mechanica, setting forth the law bearing his name.
March 18 - Jacques de Molay, the 23rd and the last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, is burned at the stake.
January-June. June 21 - The Incident at Honnō-ji occurs in Kyoto, Japan.
From this year until 1650, sixteen million kilograms of silver and 185,000 kilograms of gold will enter the port of Seville.
July-December. October - William Congreve's comedy The Double-Dealer is first performed at the Theatre Royal, Drury Lane, London.
January-June. June 27 - Patriarch Cyril of Constantinople is deposed for high treason and strangled and thrown into the sea by Janissaries on Ottoman Sultan Murad IV's command.
January-March. March 20 - At Sing Sing prison in Ossining, New York, Martha M. Place becomes the first woman executed in an electric chair.
August 15 - Michael VIII Palaeologus is crowned Byzantine emperor in Constantinople.
Undated. King Francis I of France issues an ordinance that places the whole of France under the jurisdiction of the royal law courts and makes French the language of those courts.
July-December. August 8 - English explorer John Davis enters Cumberland Sound in Baffin Island in his quest for the Northwest Passage.
Pope Pius V expels most of the prostitutes from Rome.
July-September. September 19 - William Lloyd Garrison publishes Angelina Grimké's anti-slavery letter in The Liberator.
Henry Briggs publishes Arithmetica Logarithmica.
Publications. Immanuel Kant - Observations on the Feeling of the Beautiful and Sublime (Beobachtungen über das Gefühl des Schönen und Erhabenen)
January-March. March 7 - Shrigley Abduction: Ellen Turner, a wealthy heiress in Cheshire, England, is abducted by Edward Gibbon Wakefield, the future politician in colonial New Zealand.
July-December. December - Louis XII makes peace with the Pope and Spain.
Emperor Go-Sanjō ascends to the throne of Japan.
Perkin Warbeck claims to be the son of King Edward IV of England at the court of Burgundy.
The first official translation of the entire Bible into Swedish is made.
July-December. September 7 - The city of Boston, Massachusetts is founded.
January-June. January 1 - Minimum date value for a datetime field in SQL Server (up to version 2005) due to it being the first full year after Britain adopted the Gregorian calendar.
October
July-December. July - Deventer is captured by the Dutch under Maurice of Nassau.
Europe. June 29 - Romanos IV Diogenes, deposed ruler of the Byzantine Empire, is blinded and sent into exile at the Monastery of the Transfiguration, Kinaliada.
July-December November 30. Sucre, Bolivia, is founded under the name Ciudad de la Plata de la Nueva Toledo

July-December. September 14 - Eighty Years' War: After a 5 month long siege, 's-Hertogenbosch surrenders to Frederick Henry. As a result of the capture of this key fortress, Spain's situation along the Spanish-Dutch border worsens greatly.
The first recorded Welsh Eisteddfod is held by Rhys ap Gruffydd at Cardigan.
January-June. June 4 - Great Upheaval: New England planters arrive to claim land in Nova Scotia taken from the Acadians.
April 23 – British Empire Exhibition opens. It was the largest colonial exhibition with 58 countries of the empire dramatically represented.
Henry II prohibits English students from attending the University of Paris; many settle at the University of Oxford.

November 21 - Irish War of Independence: Bloody Sunday: The Irish Republican Army, on the instructions of Michael Collins, shoot dead the "Cairo gang", fourteen British undercover agents in Dublin, most in their homes. Later that day in retaliation the Auxiliary Division of the Royal Irish Constabulary open fire on a crowd at a Gaelic Athletic Association Football match in Croke Park, killing thirteen spectators and one player and wounding 60. Three men are shot this night in Dublin Castle "while trying to escape".
January-March. February 7 - The play La vida alegre y muerte triste by dramatist José Echegaray opens.
July-December. September-October - Battle of Khotyn: Polish troops hold off a large Ottoman army for over a month.
The Bosnian nobility dethrone Queen Jelena Gruba and replace her with King Stjepan Ostoja.
The Wilmington and Raleigh Railroad is chartered in Wilmington, North Carolina.
November November 1. A broadcasting license fee of ten shillings is introduced in the United Kingdom.
The Académie française publishes the first complete edition of its Dictionnaire in Paris.
Leon Battista Alberti's De Re Aedificatoria (written 1443-52 and published posthumously) becomes the first printed work on architecture.
Napoleon Bonaparte becomes a lieutenant in the French artillery.
Undated. The Al Bu Falah move to Abu Dhabi.

July-December. November 10 (19 Brumaire) - A remnant of the Council of Ancients in France abolishes the Constitution of the Year III, and ordains the French Consulate with Napoleon as First Consul with the Constitution of the Year VIII.
Jayavarman VII, the king of Cambodia, founds the temple of Ta Prohm.
Manuel I Comnenus orders all the Venetians in the Byzantine Empire to be arrested and their property confiscated.
September 30 - Treaty of Ayton establishes a seven-year peace between England and Scotland.
Covenanters meet at Muchalls Castle to compose responses to the Bishops of Aberdeen.
April 15 - The United Kingdom's Prince of Wales visits the Japanese paramilitary youth group Seinendan in annexed Korea.
The Clontarf Cricket Club is established. The 2008 2nd XI calls their assault on all Senior II competitions "Operation 1876" in honour of this fantastic year.
July-December. July - The Hanseatic League, after 400 years of operation, holds its last official meeting in Lübeck.
January-June. April 5 - Sir Henry Collins, Earl Nick Rollings and Callum of Brown released from Snow Hill Police Dungeons after charge of fraud suspended.
March 20 - Sung Chiao-jen, a founder of the Chinese nationalist party (Kuomintang), is wounded in an assassination attempt and dies two days later.

July-December. August 22 - The Duke of Alba is sent to the Netherlands with a strong Spanish force to suppress unrest there. He replaces Margaret of Parma as Governor of the Netherlands. Prince William of Orange is outlawed, and Count Lamoral of Egmont imprisoned.

Celia Fiennes noblewoman and traveller, begins her journeys across Britain, in a venture that would prove to be her life's work. Her aim was to chronicle the towns, cities and great houses of the country. Her travels continued until at least 1712, and would take her to every county in England, though the main body of her journal was not written until the year 1702.
Europe. September 28 - James I of Aragon captures the city of Valencia from the Moors, who retreat to Granada.
December - First Barons' War: Alexander II of Scotland invades northern England.
January-June. January 7 - Pope Pius V succeeds Pope Pius IV as the 225th pope.

February 22 - King Charles VIII of France enters Naples to claim the city's throne. A few months later, he decides to return to France, and leaves Naples with most of his army, leaving a force under his cousin Gilbert, Count of Montpensier as viceroy. Syphilis is first definitely recorded during this invasion.
January-June. May 22 - Francis repudiates the Treaty of Madrid and forms the League of Cognac against Charles, including the Pope, Milan, Venice, and Florence.
July-December. October 7 - The first biography of Nicolaus Copernicus (d.1543) is completed by Bernardino Baldi.
Europe. Sancho IV of Castile captures Tarifa from the Moors.
July-August. August 30 - In Martinique, Mount Pelée erupts again, destroying the town of Morne-Rouge causing 1000 deaths.
Early Spring - Joseph Smith, Jr. receives his First Vision in Palmyra, New York.

January-March. March 15 - A German naval force shells a village in Samoa, destroying some American property; three American warships enter the Samoan harbor and prepare to fire on the three German warships found there. Before guns are fired, the 1889 Apia cyclone blows in and sinks all the ships, American and German. A compulsory armistice is called because of the lack of warships.
South Asia. Battle of Kennagal: The Hoysala Empire defeats the Chalukya.
March 5 – Italian forces are the first to use airships for a military purpose, using them for reconnaissance west of Tripoli, Libya, behind Turkish lines.
June 1 - Battle of San Romano: Florence defeats Siena.
July-September. August 9 - The Aberdeen Act is signed as part of the abolition of the African slave trade.
July-December. July 3 - A lightning strike causes a major fire at Portsmouth Royal Dockyard in England.
May 11 - The Mountainous Republic of the Northern Caucasus is officially established.
Nathan B. Stubblefield demonstrates his mobile phone device in Kentucky.
According to a popular legend, Prince Madog of Gwynedd reaches North America in what is present-day Alabama.
The world's first complex machine mass-produced from interchangeable parts, Eli Terry's wooden pillar-and-scroll clock, comes off the production line in Plymouth, Connecticut.
Johann Heinrich Alsted's Encyclopaedia septem tomis distincta is published.
Hananchi succeeds Min as King of Hokuzan in present-day north Okinawa, Japan.
John III Ducas Vatatzes becomes Byzantine Emperor (in the Empire of Nicaea).

February 28 - Ch'oe Pu (1454-1504), the Korean Commissioner of Registers for the island of Cheju, shipwrecks on the southeast coast of China in Taizhou, Zhejiang, during the Ming Dynasty. From then until July 12 he and his crew are hosted by Chinese military courier officers to travel along the Grand Canal of China, all the way to Beijing, and then finally back across the Yalu River into Korea. His written commentary on Chinese customs, foreign and domestic trade, and transport in places such as Hangzhou and Suzhou are valuable records of Ming era culture and commerce.
July-September. August 16 - War of 1812: American General William Hull surrenders Fort Detroit without a fight to the British Army.
January-June. April 2 - The town of Raynham, Massachusetts in Bristol County is entered as a new town by the governor and court of Massachusetts, New England, America.
A serious fire occurs at St Paul's Cathedral in London.

October-December. November 15 - American Civil War - Sherman's March to the Sea begins: Union General Sherman burns Atlanta and starts to move south, causing extensive devastation to crops and mills and living off the land.
Jacob ben Machir is appointed dean of the medical school at Montpellier.
July-September. July 23 - Robert Emmet's uprising in Ireland begins.
July-December. October - An Algerian military campaign by Charles V of Spain (Habsburg) is unsuccessful.
Dragoş becomes voivode of Moldova.
